      "shortest": true,
      "solution": "#include <stdio.h>\n\n/* Integers from the input */\nint h, p, q;\n\n/* Computed amount of blocks of height P that are in the tower */\nint x;\n\nint main(void) {\n    /* Read H, P and Q from the input */\n    scanf(\"%d%d%d\", &h, &p, &q);\n\n    /* Assume that the tower has the maximum possible number of blocks of\n       height P and no blocks of height Q */\n    x = h/p;\n\n    /* Keep removing blocks of height P until it is possible to construct\n       the remaining height of the tower using blocks of height Q */\n    while ((h - x*p) % q && x >= 0) x -= 1;\n\n    /* If the value of X is negative the tower is inconstructible */\n    if (x < 0) printf(\"0\\n\");\n\n    /* Otherwise it is constructible and we will have computed the optimal\n       number of blocks of each height (maximizes total number of blocks) */\n    else printf(\"%d\\n\", x + (h - x*p)/q);\n}",
      "statement": "I want to construct a tower of height [[H]] by stacking blocks in a straight line going upwards.\n\nHowever I only have two types of blocks: blocks of height [[P]] and blocks of height [[Q]], with [[P]] ≤ [[Q]].\n\nIf any combination of these two types of blocks is allowed, what is the <<maximum>> amount of blocks that can be used to construct the tower?\n\nIf it is impossible to construct the tower, the output should be {{0}}.",
